{{Infobox glacier | name = Apusiaajik Glacier | photo = Apusiaajik-glacier.jpg | photo_caption = Apusiaajik Glacier seen from [[Kulusuk Island]] | type = Mountain glacier | map = Greenland | map_caption = Location in Greenland | map_size = 240 | label = Apusiaajik Glacier | location = [[Apusiaajik Island]], [[Sermersooq]], [[Greenland]] | coordinates = {{coord|65|39|10|N|37|03|25|W|region:AQ|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | coords_ref = | area = | length = | thickness = | terminus = [[Torsuut Tunoq]], [[North Atlantic]] | status = }}
'''Apusiaajik Glacier''' is a tidewater [[glacier]] on the uninhabited [[Apusiaajik Island]] in the [[Sermersooq]] municipality on the southeastern shore of [[Greenland]].<ref name="saga">Tasiilaq, Saga Map, Tage Schjøtt, 1992</ref>
== Tourism == During summer, the glacier edge is a popular tourist destination for boat trips from [[Tasiilaq]] and [[Kulusuk]].<ref name="lp">{{cite book|last=O'Carroll|first=Etain|title=Greenland and the Arctic|publisher=[[Lonely Planet]] |pages=204–205|year=2005|isbn=1-74059-095-3}}</ref> During winter it is possible to reach the front of the glacier crossing the frozen [[Torsuut Tunoq]] sound on foot or on [[snowmobile]].
== References == {{commonscat|Apusiaajik Glacier}} {{reflist}}
[[Category:Glaciers of Greenland]] {{Glaciology-stub}}

'''Aqueous geochemistry''' studies the role of various elements in [[drainage basin|watershed]]s, including copper, sulfur, and mercury. Researchers in this field also study how elemental fluxes are exchanged through interactions between the [[atmosphere]], the earth or soil (terrestrial interactions) and bodies of water (aquatic interactions).

Work in the field of aqueous geochemistry has also studied the prevalence of [[rare earth elements]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Wood|first1=Scott A.|title=The aqueous geochemistry of the rare-earth elements and yttrium|journal=Chemical Geology|volume=82|pages=159–186|doi=10.1016/0009-2541(90)90080-Q|year=1990}}</ref> [[nuclear waste]] products,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kaszuba|first1=John P.|last2=Runde|first2=Wolfgang H.|title=The Aqueous Geochemistry of Neptunium:  Dynamic Control of Soluble Concentrations with Applications to Nuclear Waste Disposal|journal=Environmental Science & Technology|volume=33|issue=24|pages=4427–4433|doi=10.1021/es990470x|year=1999}}</ref> and [[hydrocarbon]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Seewald|first1=Jeffrey S|title=Aqueous geochemistry of low molecular weight hydrocarbons at elevated temperatures and pressures: constraints from mineral buffered laboratory experiments|journal=Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta|volume=65|issue=10|pages=1641–1664|doi=10.1016/S0016-7037(01)00544-0|year=2001}}</ref>

